To investigate whether other analytes cause interference, the NCDs@ZIF-L nanocomposite was tested for PA in the presence of different aromatic, nitro interferences and heavy metals at concentrations 4 µM (
Fig. S5
). For the aromatic interferences, the nanocomposite shows a good sensing performance in terms of sensitivity and selectivity towards PA as shown in Fig. 6 a. As clearly seen, after the addition of PA to different analytes, the quenching increases, which demonstrates the better selectivity of PA by NCDs@ZIF-L nanocomposite (Fig. 6). Further, the sensitivity of nanocomposite was also tested towards PA in the presence of other interfered heavy metal ions (Fig. 6b). The NCDs@ZIF-L nanocomposite still shows a higher quenching emission in the presence of heavy metal interferences and the absence of PA. After the addition of PA in the aqueous solution-containing heavy metal interferences, the relative fluorescence intensity of the NCDs@ZIF-L exhibits a remarkable increase in quenching, implying that our nanocomposite exhibits a relatively high sensitivity towards PA, despite the presence of other analytes interferences. These results reveal that the synthesized nanocomposite shows a good sensing performance for PA. The effect of the nanocomposite towards PA for realistic applications was also measured. PA was spiked at different concentrations in tap water to the solution containing nanocomposite (Table S4). R% and RSD% were applied and calculated from Eq. (3). It was found that R% ranges in 91.3–102 % and RSD% ranges were less than 5 % which indicates its high feasibility towards PA in real samples. After adsorption/desorption cycles, the stability of the repurposed NCDs@ZIF-L nanocomposite demonstrated that the structural functionality of the nanocomposite could be retained for reuse/cycles, allowing for a reduction in PA concentration, the potential for low-cost decontamination, and a decrease in wastes and hazardous residues that pose a risk to people and the environment. Fig. 6(c, d) showed the SEM images of the NCDs@ZIF-L nanocomposite after reuse, which showed that the nanocomposite, after being reused, contains a constant shape with few irregular edges. Additionally, NCDs incorporated ZIF-L are still retained and show good crystallinity after reuse (Fig. 6d), demonstrating the stability of nanocomposite, thereby offering numerous active sites throughout their surface that are capable of binding target PA in aqueous solutions in the presence of other analytes interferences.
